---

### ðŸŸ¢ Concept Overview
Cloud Computing is the on-demand delivery of IT resources (compute, storage, databases) via the internet with pay-as-you-go pricing. 
It eliminates the need to manage physical hardware.

### ðŸ”‘ Core Pillars (NIST Model)
* **On-Demand Self-Service:** Provision resources instantly without human intervention.
* **Broad Network Access:** Services are accessible over the network via standard mechanisms.
* **Resource Pooling:** Computing resources are pooled to serve multiple consumers (Multi-tenancy).
* **Rapid Elasticity:** Capabilities can be elastically provisioned and released to scale rapidly with demand.
* **Measured Service:** Resource usage is automatically monitored and controlled for transparent billing.

### ðŸ“Š Comparison: On-Premise vs. Cloud
| Feature | On-Premise IT | Cloud Computing |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Cost Model** | CapEx (High Upfront) | OpEx (Pay-as-you-use) |
| **Agility** | Low (Weeks to deploy) | High (Minutes to deploy) |
| **Scalability** | Manual & Limited | Automated & Infinite |
| **Maintenance** | In-house Responsibility | Provider Managed |

### ðŸ’¡ Key Takeaway
The transition to cloud is a shift from **Physical Infrastructure** to **Software-Defined Infrastructure**. 
It allows developers to focus on code and innovation rather than hardware procurement and data center maintenance.
